Chapter 8 — Allostery and Conformational Dynamics

8.1 The Concept of Allostery

Allostery refers to regulation of protein function by binding at a site distinct from the active site. It is fundamental to cellular signaling, metabolism, and gene regulation.

Two classical models describe allostery :

MWC model (Monod-Wyman-Changeux, 1965) : Proteins exist in equilibrium between two conformational states (tense and relaxed). Ligands bind preferentially to one state, shifting the equilibrium. All subunits change conformation concertedly.

KNF model (Koshland-Némethy-Filmer, 1966) : Ligand binding induces conformational change in the bound subunit, which affects neighboring subunits sequentially. There is no requirement for all subunits to change together.

These models represent limiting cases; real proteins often exhibit behavior between them .

8.2 The Ensemble View of Allostery

Modern views recognize that proteins exist as ensembles of conformations. The population of each state is determined by its free energy:

P_i = \frac{e^{-G_i/k_B T}}{Z}, \quad Z = \sum_i e^{-G_i/k_B T}

Allostery works by changing these populations .

Ligand binding to a site with binding energy $\Delta G_{\text{bind}}$ shifts the free energy of all states that are competent to bind. If state $i$ has binding energy $\Delta G_{\text{bind},i}$, its population becomes:

P_i^{\text{ligand}} = \frac{e^{-(G_i + \Delta G_{\text{bind},i})/k_B T}}{Z'}

The effect propagates because states are interconnected through the energy landscape.

8.3 Quantifying Allosteric Coupling

The strength of allosteric coupling between two sites can be quantified by mutual information:

I(A;B) = \sum_{a,b} p(a,b) \log_2 \frac{p(a,b)}{p(a)p(b)}

where $A$ and $B$ are conformational states or ligand binding states at the two sites.

Experimentally, double mutant cycles measure energetic coupling. For mutations at sites $i$ and $j$, the coupling energy is:

\Delta\Delta G_{\text{int}} = \Delta G_{i,j} - \Delta G_i - \Delta G_j + \Delta G_{\text{wt}}

where $\Delta G_{i,j}$ is the effect of both mutations together, and $\Delta G_i$, $\Delta G_j$ are individual effects. Non-zero $\Delta\Delta G_{\text{int}}$ indicates interaction between sites .

8.4 Allosteric Landscapes

Recent deep mutational scanning studies have mapped allosteric landscapes for several proteins . By measuring the effects of thousands of mutations on function, researchers can identify networks of residues that couple distant sites.

For a PDZ domain, Faure et al. (2026) measured free energy changes for >190,000 variants and identified ~7000 energetic couplings . They found that domain extensions (additional structural elements) can dramatically reshape the allosteric landscape, creating new opportunities for regulation.

The allosteric connectivity can be represented as a graph where nodes are residues and edges represent energetic coupling. Network analysis reveals hubs and modules that correspond to functional units.

8.5 Dynamics and Allostery

Allostery often involves changes in protein dynamics even without large structural changes. This "dynamic allostery" or "entropy-driven allostery" occurs when ligand binding alters the spectrum of fluctuations.

The change in conformational entropy can be estimated from NMR relaxation experiments. The entropy change upon ligand binding:

\Delta S_{\text{conf}} = -R \sum_i \int J_i(\omega) \ln J_i(\omega) d\omega

where $J_i(\omega)$ is the spectral density function for residue $i$.

8.6 Evolutionary Implications

Allosteric networks are shaped by evolution. Residues that are energetically coupled tend to be conserved across protein families, suggesting they are functionally important .

The "evolvability" of allostery—the ability to acquire new regulatory connections—may depend on the presence of flexible regions and surface-exposed sites that can couple to new inputs. Domain extensions provide raw material for evolutionary innovation .

