Chapter 10 — DNA as Digital Information Storage

10.1 The Molecular Hard Drive

DNA is the primary information storage medium of life. From an information-theoretic perspective, it is a quaternary digital system with four nucleotide states: adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G), and thymine (T). Unlike human-engineered binary storage (0,1), nature evolved a base‑4 architecture.

The information capacity per nucleotide is:

I_{\text{per nt}} = \log_2 4 = 2 \text{ bits}

For a genome of length $L$ base pairs, the maximum information content is:

I_{\text{genome}} = 2L \text{ bits}

The human genome contains approximately $3.2 \times 10^9$ base pairs, yielding a theoretical maximum of $6.4 \times 10^9$ bits—roughly 800 megabytes of uncompressed digital data .

10.2 Physical Storage Density

DNA achieves extraordinary volumetric density. Theoretical calculations and experimental demonstrations show that DNA can store approximately 215 petabytes per gram . This density exceeds any human-engineered storage medium by orders of magnitude.

The information density per cubic nanometer can be estimated from the physical dimensions of the double helix. With a diameter of 2 nm and a rise of 0.34 nm per base pair, each base pair occupies a volume of approximately:

V_{\text{bp}} \approx \pi (1 \text{ nm})^2 \times 0.34 \text{ nm} \approx 1.07 \text{ nm}^3

Thus, the volumetric density is:

\rho_{\text{info}} = \frac{2 \text{ bits}}{1.07 \text{ nm}^3} \approx 1.87 \text{ bits/nm}^3

This is the physical limit imposed by molecular geometry—a fundamental constraint on biological information storage.

10.3 Thermodynamic Stability and Persistence

The double helix structure protects genetic information through two complementary mechanisms:

Hydrophobic stacking: The planar aromatic rings of bases stack in the helix interior, excluding water and providing van der Waals stabilization of approximately $2\text{--}4$ kcal/mol per base pair.

Complementary hydrogen bonding: Watson‑Crick pairing (A‑T with two hydrogen bonds, G‑C with three) adds specificity and additional stabilization:

\Delta G_{\text{H-bond}} \approx 1\text{--}3 \text{ kcal/mol per bond}

The total free energy of duplex formation for a sequence of length $N$ is approximately:

\Delta G_{\text{duplex}} = \sum_{i=1}^{N-1} \Delta G_{\text{stack}}(i, i+1) + \Delta G_{\text{init}}

where nearest-neighbor parameters have been experimentally determined .

Despite this stability, DNA is subject to spontaneous chemical damage. The most common lesion is depurination—hydrolysis of the glycosidic bond linking a purine base to deoxyribose. The rate constant at physiological pH and temperature is approximately:

k_{\text{depur}} \approx 3 \times 10^{-11} \text{ s}^{-1}

corresponding to a half-life of roughly 700 years per purine under ideal conditions. In living cells, this damage is constantly repaired, but in dead tissue, it limits the persistence of retrievable DNA to thousands or tens of thousands of years.

10.4 DNA as a Communication Channel

The DNA storage channel can be modeled information-theoretically. Information is synthesized onto many short DNA strands, and each strand may be copied multiple times during sequencing. The receiver draws strands in an uncontrollable manner—some strands may be drawn multiple times, others not at all—and the obtained strands may contain errors .

The Shannon capacity of this channel, representing the maximum achievable information density per nucleotide for reliable storage, has been bounded and achievability demonstrated for a large range of parameters . A practical decoder clusters received strands by similarity and estimates original sequences based on these clusters .

This perspective—treating the genome as a communication channel with error-correcting codes—provides the mathematical foundation for understanding how life preserves information across generations.

