Chapter 11 — Replication: The High-Fidelity Copy Protocol

11.1 The Replication Algorithm

DNA replication is a semi-conservative process: each daughter duplex contains one parental strand and one newly synthesized strand. The enzyme DNA polymerase catalyzes nucleotide addition, reading the template strand and incorporating complementary nucleotides.

The polymerization reaction follows Michaelis‑Menten kinetics:

v = \frac{k_{\text{cat}} [\text{DNA}] [\text{dNTP}]}{K_m + [\text{dNTP}]}

where $k_{\text{cat}}$ is the catalytic rate constant, $K_m$ is the Michaelis constant for nucleotide incorporation, and dNTP represents deoxynucleoside triphosphates.

Replication speed (bandwidth) varies by organism. In Escherichia coli, DNA polymerase III holoenzyme achieves approximately 1000 nucleotides per second per replication fork. The entire $4.6 \times 10^6$ bp genome replicates in about 40 minutes .

11.2 Intrinsic Error Rates

DNA polymerase occasionally incorporates incorrect nucleotides. The baseline misincorporation rate, prior to any correction mechanisms, is approximately:

\mu_{\text{baseline}} \approx 10^{-4} \text{ to } 10^{-5} \text{ per base per replication}

This means that for every 10,000 to 100,000 nucleotides added, one is incorrect .

The error rate varies depending on the specific polymerase and the type of mismatch. Experimental measurements of non‑enzymatic template-directed polymerization show that misincorporation rates can range from $0.8\%$ to $7.6\%$ depending on base composition, with G‑C rich templates exhibiting lower error rates .

11.3 Proofreading: The "Undo" Command

Many DNA polymerases possess 3′→5′ exonuclease activity, which allows them to remove a newly added nucleotide if it is incorrect. This proofreading function acts as an immediate "undo" command.

When a mismatch occurs, the polymerase stalls because the misaligned terminus cannot adopt the correct conformation for the next addition. This stalling allows time for the exonuclease domain to remove the incorrect nucleotide. The corrected error rate after proofreading is:

\mu_{\text{proofread}} \approx \mu_{\text{baseline}} \times \text{(fraction of errors proofread)}

Experimental studies show that proofreading corrects greater than 95% of errors made by DNA polymerase . Thus, the error rate after proofreading is approximately:

\mu_{\text{proofread}} \approx 10^{-5} \times 0.05 = 5 \times 10^{-7}

or $10^{-6}$ to $10^{-7}$ per base per replication .

11.4 Mismatch Repair: Post-Replication Checksum

After replication, a second system scans the newly synthesized DNA for errors that escaped proofreading. Mismatch repair (MMR) recognizes distortions in the helix caused by mismatched base pairs and excises a segment of the newly synthesized strand, using the parental strand as a template for resynthesis.

The cell must distinguish the newly synthesized strand (which may contain errors) from the parental template. In many bacteria, this discrimination is achieved by transient undermethylation of the nascent strand. The parental strand is methylated at specific sequences, while the new strand is not yet methylated, providing a temporal marker .

Mismatch repair reduces the final error rate to approximately:

\mu_{\text{final}} \approx 10^{-9} \text{ to } 10^{-10} \text{ per base per replication}

This represents a 100,000‑fold improvement over the baseline error rate .

11.5 The Error Hierarchy

The complete error correction cascade can be summarized:

Stage Error Rate Reduction Factor
Baseline misincorporation $10^{-4} - 10^{-5}$ 1×
After proofreading $10^{-6} - 10^{-7}$ ~100×
After mismatch repair $10^{-9} - 10^{-10}$ ~1000×

This hierarchy ensures that the "life software" remains stable across billions of years of evolution .

11.6 The Speed‑Accuracy Trade‑off

Replication faces a fundamental trade‑off between speed and accuracy. Increasing speed tends to decrease fidelity, while maximizing accuracy slows replication. Natural selection has optimized this trade‑off differently in various organisms.

The replication complex achieves its remarkable fidelity through a combination of:

· Geometric selection: The active site favors correctly paired nucleotides
· Kinetic discrimination: Incorrect nucleotides bind more weakly and dissociate faster
· Exonucleolytic proofreading: Removal of misincorporated bases
· Post‑replicative repair: Second‑pass error checking

This multi‑layer error correction is conceptually analogous to error-correcting codes in digital communication systems, where redundant information and parity checks ensure data integrity across noisy channels .

