Chapter 15 — Chemiosmosis: The Proton Circuit

15.1 The Chemiosmotic Theory

In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed the chemiosmotic hypothesis, which revolutionized our understanding of energy transduction. The theory states that electron transport chains generate a proton gradient across a membrane, and the energy stored in this gradient drives ATP synthesis .

The key insight was recognizing that the connection between electron transport and ATP synthesis is not a mysterious chemical messenger but an electrochemical gradient of protons. Mitchell realized that the chemical had to be the one associated with redox phenomena—the proton—because most redox reactions are accompanied by proton transfers .

15.2 The Electron Transport Chain as a Proton Pump

In mitochondria, high-energy electrons from NADH and FADH₂ (derived from glucose and fat oxidation) pass through a series of protein complexes (I–IV) embedded in the inner mitochondrial membrane. As electrons move through these complexes, their energy is used to pump protons from the matrix to the intermembrane space.

For each NADH oxidized, approximately 10 protons are pumped across the membrane. For FADH₂, which enters at a later complex, approximately 6 protons are pumped .

15.3 The Proton Motive Force (PMF)

The pumping of protons creates both a concentration gradient and an electrical gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane:

· Chemical potential: Higher proton concentration in the intermembrane space (lower pH) than in the matrix
· Electrical potential: Positive charge accumulation in the intermembrane space, negative charge in the matrix

Together, these constitute the proton motive force (PMF) , defined as :

\Delta p = \Delta \Psi - \frac{2.303 RT}{F} \Delta \text{pH}

where:

· $\Delta \Psi$ is the transmembrane electrical potential (typically 150–180 mV, positive outside)
· $\Delta \text{pH}$ is the pH difference (typically 0.5–1.0 units, acidic outside)
· $R$ is the gas constant (8.314 J/mol·K)
· $T$ is the absolute temperature (K)
· $F$ is the Faraday constant (96,485 C/mol)

The free energy stored in the proton gradient per mole of protons is :

\Delta G = RT \ln \frac{[\text{H}^+]_{\text{out}}}{[\text{H}^+]_{\text{in}}} + F \Delta \Psi = 2.303 RT \Delta \text{pH} + F \Delta \Psi

For actively respiring mitochondria with $\Delta \Psi \approx 0.15$ V and $\Delta \text{pH} \approx 0.75$:

\Delta G \approx (5 + 15) \text{ kJ/mol} = 20 \text{ kJ/mol per proton}

This means each proton flowing back into the matrix can provide approximately 20 kJ/mol of free energy to drive ATP synthesis.

The proton motive force delivers approximately 0.2 eV of energy per proton at the molecular scale .

15.4 Efficiency of Energy Conservation

The oxidation of NADH by oxygen releases approximately 220 kJ/mol of free energy. With 10 protons pumped per NADH, and each proton storing 20 kJ/mol, the energy conserved in the proton gradient is:

10 \text{ protons} \times 20 \text{ kJ/mol·proton} = 200 \text{ kJ/mol}

Thus, approximately 90% of the energy from NADH oxidation is conserved in the proton gradient before ATP synthesis . This remarkable efficiency highlights the evolutionary optimization of the chemiosmotic system.

