Chapter 29 — Macroevolution and Phylogenetics

29.1 Phylogenetic Trees as Information Structures

A phylogenetic tree represents the evolutionary history of a group of organisms. It is an information structure encoding:

· Branching order (speciation events)
· Branch lengths (time or genetic distance)
· Topology (relatedness)

The information content of a phylogeny can be quantified using tree entropy measures.

29.2 Molecular Clock

The molecular clock hypothesis states that sequence evolution occurs at an approximately constant rate over time. For a given gene, the number of substitutions $K$ between two species is proportional to divergence time $T$:

K = 2\mu T

where $\mu$ is the substitution rate per lineage per year. This allows phylogenetic trees to be calibrated in absolute time.

29.3 Phylogenetic Comparative Methods

Phylogenetic trees are essential for comparative biology, allowing researchers to account for shared evolutionary history when analyzing trait correlations. The phylogenetic generalized least squares (PGLS) model is:

\mathbf{Y} = \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}, \quad \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2 \mathbf{C})

where $\mathbf{C}$ is a covariance matrix derived from the phylogeny.

