Chapter 30 — Synthesis: Evolution as Information Accumulation

30.1 The Fitness Flux Theorem

Mustonen and Lässig introduced the concept of fitness flux—the cumulative selective effect of phenotypic changes along an evolutionary trajectory . For a population history $\Gamma_0, \ldots, \Gamma_M$ at times $t_0,\ldots,t_M$, the fitness flux is:

\Phi = \sum_{i=1}^M \delta\Gamma_i \, \partial_{\Gamma_i} F(\Gamma_i, t_i)

Remarkably, this quantity relates to entropy production in statistical physics . The Kullback-Leibler divergence between forward and backward trajectories satisfies:

\langle 2N\Phi \rangle = KL(P|P_T) + \text{boundary terms}

This is the evolutionary fluctuation theorem, connecting adaptive evolution to the thermodynamics of information.

30.2 The Landauer Limit of Evolution

Every bit of information fixed by selection requires a minimum energy dissipation, given by the Landauer limit $k_B T \ln 2$. For a population of size $N$ over $T$ generations, the total information fixed is:

I_{\text{fix}} = \sum_{\text{fixations}} \log_2\left(\frac{1}{p_{\text{neutral}}}\right) \text{ bits}

The minimum energy cost is $E_{\min} = I_{\text{fix}} k_B T \ln 2$. Real populations dissipate far more energy due to:

· Imperfect efficiency of selection
· Metabolic costs of reproduction
· Genetic load from deleterious mutations
· Thermodynamic costs of proofreading

30.3 The Arrow of Evolutionary Time

Evolution has a direction: increasing complexity, information, and adaptation over time. This arrow of evolutionary time parallels the thermodynamic arrow:

· Entropy increases in isolated systems
· Information (fitness) increases in evolving populations

The analogy is not perfect—environments change, fitness peaks move—but the statistical tendency is clear: populations accumulate information about their environments.

30.4 From Evolution to Learning

Evolution is a form of learning—a population learns about its environment through the trial-and-error process of mutation and selection. The parallels with neural learning are striking:

Evolutionary Process Neural Analog
Mutation Random weight perturbation
Selection Reinforcement of successful patterns
Recombination Crossover of network modules
Fitness Reward signal
Generations Training epochs

This connection will be explored in Part VII, where we examine how neural systems implement similar learning algorithms on much faster timescales.

